Dialogue: 0,0:00:01.36,0:00:03.36,Default,,0,0,0,,A discussion of riches
Dialogue: 0,0:00:03.36,0:00:05.78,Default,,0,0,0,,often centers on the danger
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.78,0:00:07.99,Default,,0,0,0,,of making material wealth
Dialogue: 0,0:00:07.99,0:00:10.53,Default,,0,0,0,,the main thing in our life.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:10.53,0:00:12.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Our text today is about riches,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:12.99,0:00:16.75,Default,,0,0,0,,but the focus is on how we use
Dialogue: 0,0:00:16.75,0:00:18.96,Default,,0,0,0,,the things that we possess.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:18.96,0:00:23.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s go back to our text at Luke 16:9\Nand read it once again.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:23.96,0:00:26.51,Default,,0,0,0,,It says:\N“Also, I say to you:
Dialogue: 0,0:00:26.51,0:00:31.01,Default,,0,0,0,,“Make friends for yourselves\Nby means of the unrighteous riches,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:31.01,0:00:33.27,Default,,0,0,0,,“so that when such fail,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:33.27,0:00:36.94,Default,,0,0,0,,they may receive you\Ninto the everlasting dwelling places.”
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.94,0:00:40.82,Default,,0,0,0,,There are certain aspects of this text
Dialogue: 0,0:00:40.82,0:00:44.15,Default,,0,0,0,,that some have found difficult to understand.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.15,0:00:46.15,Default,,0,0,0,,For example,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.15,0:00:48.91,Default,,0,0,0,,why would a Christian even be in possession
Dialogue: 0,0:00:48.91,0:00:52.49,Default,,0,0,0,,of unrighteous riches?
Dialogue: 0,0:00:52.49,0:00:56.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Who are referred to by the pronoun “they”?
Dialogue: 0,0:00:56.87,0:01:01.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Also, what application\Nis there in this illustration for us?
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.30,0:01:06.26,Default,,0,0,0,,To clarify matters,\Nit will help us to look at the context.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:06.26,0:01:09.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Verses 1 through 8\Nof Luke chapter 16
Dialogue: 0,0:01:09.51,0:01:14.02,Default,,0,0,0,,contain the illustration\Nof the steward and the unrighteous riches.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:14.02,0:01:16.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Verses 9 to 13
Dialogue: 0,0:01:16.15,0:01:20.15,Default,,0,0,0,,provide the application of the illustration.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.15,0:01:24.28,Default,,0,0,0,,And that application includes the principles
Dialogue: 0,0:01:24.28,0:01:27.74,Default,,0,0,0,,that ‘the person faithful in least\Nis faithful in much’
Dialogue: 0,0:01:27.74,0:01:32.75,Default,,0,0,0,,and also that we “cannot slave for God\Nand for Riches.”
Dialogue: 0,0:01:32.75,0:01:36.21,Default,,0,0,0,,To learn how we can benefit\Nfrom this teaching of Jesus,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:36.21,0:01:39.05,Default,,0,0,0,,let’s consider three things.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.05,0:01:43.76,Default,,0,0,0,,First of all,\Nwe will examine the illustration.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.76,0:01:48.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Second, we will identify the elements.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:48.39,0:01:52.19,Default,,0,0,0,,And third, we’ll make the application.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.19,0:01:55.02,Default,,0,0,0,,So first of all,\Nlet’s examine the illustration.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.02,0:01:59.07,Default,,0,0,0,,If we look at Luke 16:1,\Nit talks about a steward.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.07,0:02:04.07,Default,,0,0,0,,If we look at the footnote,\Nit says this could be a “house manager.”
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.07,0:02:08.54,Default,,0,0,0,,So it is someone who’s entrusted\Nwith a good deal of responsibility.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.54,0:02:11.00,Default,,0,0,0,,But it says that he is accused
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.00,0:02:14.54,Default,,0,0,0,,of handling his master’s “goods wastefully.”
Dialogue: 0,0:02:15.67,0:02:17.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, the wording of that verse
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.67,0:02:22.09,Default,,0,0,0,,allows for the possibility\Nthat the steward was slandered.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:22.09,0:02:25.14,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s possible the charges were false.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.14,0:02:30.06,Default,,0,0,0,,But Jesus doesn’t focus\Non the reason for the steward’s dismissal.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.06,0:02:33.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Rather,\Nhe gives attention
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.15,0:02:36.15,Default,,0,0,0,,to the steward’s reaction.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:36.15,0:02:38.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Verses 2 through 7
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.15,0:02:42.70,Default,,0,0,0,,show us the reasoning of the steward\N(knowing that he’s going to be fired).
Dialogue: 0,0:02:42.70,0:02:44.70,Default,,0,0,0,,He says:\N‘I’m not strong enough to dig.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.70,0:02:46.08,Default,,0,0,0,,‘I’m ashamed to beg.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.08,0:02:48.25,Default,,0,0,0,,So how am I going to make a living?’
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.25,0:02:53.09,Default,,0,0,0,,So he decides to befriend ones\Nwho owe things to his master.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:53.09,0:02:56.30,Default,,0,0,0,,One debtor owes 100 measures of olive oil,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.30,0:03:00.64,Default,,0,0,0,,so the steward reduces that debt\Nto 50 measures.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.64,0:03:05.64,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s a reduction\Nof nearly 300 (1,100 L) gallons of olive oil.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.52,0:03:10.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Another debtor owes his master\N100 large measures of wheat.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.10,0:03:12.36,Default,,0,0,0,,He reduces that to 80.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:12.36,0:03:15.78,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s a reduction\Nof 4,000 (3,700 L) quarts of wheat.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.78,0:03:19.57,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s a substantial reduction in the debt.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.57,0:03:22.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Then if we look at verse 8,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.03,0:03:25.04,Default,,0,0,0,,the master,\Non finding out what the steward has done,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:25.04,0:03:27.04,Default,,0,0,0,,calls him “unrighteous,”
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.04,0:03:31.63,Default,,0,0,0,,and yet he commends him\Nfor acting “with practical wisdom.”
Dialogue: 0,0:03:32.55,0:03:34.88,Default,,0,0,0,,So here Jesus is not condoning
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.88,0:03:38.30,Default,,0,0,0,,or endorsing the steward’s methods,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:38.30,0:03:43.27,Default,,0,0,0,,nor is he encouraging\Ncrafty business practices.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.27,0:03:47.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus simply draws attention\Nto the need to be farsighted
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.52,0:03:51.36,Default,,0,0,0,,and to use practical wisdom.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.36,0:03:54.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let’s identify the elements.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.03,0:03:56.95,Default,,0,0,0,,We come to our text, verse 9,\Nwhere it tells us
Dialogue: 0,0:03:56.95,0:04:01.74,Default,,0,0,0,,to ‘use our unrighteous riches\Nto make friends.’
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.74,0:04:04.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Jesus doesn’t explain in detail
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.54,0:04:08.04,Default,,0,0,0,,why he refers to the riches as unrighteous.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.04,0:04:11.75,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the {\i1}{\fs16}{\fnArial}New International Version {\r}\Ngives us a hint
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.75,0:04:16.30,Default,,0,0,0,,when it calls the unrighteous riches\N“worldly wealth.”
Dialogue: 0,0:04:17.26,0:04:19.47,Default,,0,0,0,,In other words,\Nthe unrighteous riches
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.47,0:04:21.85,Default,,0,0,0,,represent material resources
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.85,0:04:26.06,Default,,0,0,0,,under the control of sinful humans.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.06,0:04:30.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Riches often serve selfish ends,\Nand they may be gained
Dialogue: 0,0:04:30.44,0:04:34.86,Default,,0,0,0,,through crafty or even illegal\Nbusiness practices.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:35.99,0:04:38.24,Default,,0,0,0,,Then Jesus states a reality.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.24,0:04:40.66,Default,,0,0,0,,He says “when such fail.”
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.66,0:04:45.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, the value of material wealth is limited,\Nand it’s temporary.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.58,0:04:48.42,Default,,0,0,0,,It can be eaten away by inflation.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:48.42,0:04:50.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Consider the value
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.63,0:04:54.43,Default,,0,0,0,,of one U.S. dollar 50 years ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.43,0:04:57.89,Default,,0,0,0,,If you had 100 dollars (U.S.) in 1969,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.89,0:05:01.85,Default,,0,0,0,,you would need 692 dollars today
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.85,0:05:04.73,Default,,0,0,0,,to have the same purchasing power.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.73,0:05:08.15,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1969,\Na gallon (4 L) of gas cost 32 cents.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:08.15,0:05:10.90,Default,,0,0,0,,A loaf of bread cost 23 cents.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.90,0:05:12.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, riches fail.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:12.90,0:05:16.45,Default,,0,0,0,,And they will definitely fail in the future.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.45,0:05:19.29,Default,,0,0,0,,Zephaniah 1:18 says:
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.29,0:05:22.46,Default,,0,0,0,,“Neither their silver nor their gold\Nwill be able to save them
Dialogue: 0,0:05:22.46,0:05:24.46,Default,,0,0,0,,in the day of Jehovah’s fury.”
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.71,0:05:27.84,Default,,0,0,0,,During the great tribulation,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.84,0:05:32.80,Default,,0,0,0,,we’re not going to be judged\Nbased on the size of our bank account.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:32.80,0:05:34.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Rather, we’re going to be judged
Dialogue: 0,0:05:34.80,0:05:38.02,Default,,0,0,0,,based on our storehouse of spiritual riches
Dialogue: 0,0:05:38.02,0:05:40.18,Default,,0,0,0,,that we have accumulated.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.18,0:05:45.19,Default,,0,0,0,,And that leads to the meaning\Nof the latter part of verse 9;
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.19,0:05:47.78,Default,,0,0,0,,it says that “they may receive you
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.78,0:05:51.16,Default,,0,0,0,,into the everlasting dwelling places.”
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.16,0:05:53.20,Default,,0,0,0,,What or who
Dialogue: 0,0:05:53.20,0:05:57.41,Default,,0,0,0,,is referred to by the word “they”?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:57.41,0:05:59.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Is it the riches?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.21,0:06:00.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Certainly not.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:00.46,0:06:03.17,Default,,0,0,0,,They’re temporary; they’re going to fail.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:03.17,0:06:07.17,Default,,0,0,0,,We have to go back to earlier in the verse\Nto find the antecedent.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.17,0:06:09.97,Default,,0,0,0,,And it is the word “friends.”
Dialogue: 0,0:06:09.97,0:06:12.43,Default,,0,0,0,,So who are these friends?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:12.43,0:06:16.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Please open your Bibles to John 3:16.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.77,0:06:21.15,Default,,0,0,0,,There are\Nonly two possibilities of individuals
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.15,0:06:24.78,Default,,0,0,0,,who can give us\Neverlasting dwelling places,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.78,0:06:27.32,Default,,0,0,0,,and they’re identified here in this verse.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.32,0:06:30.41,Default,,0,0,0,,John 3:16—it says:
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.41,0:06:32.87,Default,,0,0,0,,“For God loved the world so much
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.87,0:06:35.66,Default,,0,0,0,,“that he gave his only-begotten Son,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:35.66,0:06:38.62,Default,,0,0,0,,“so that everyone exercising faith in him
Dialogue: 0,0:06:38.62,0:06:40.63,Default,,0,0,0,,“might not be destroyed
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.63,0:06:44.05,Default,,0,0,0,,but have everlasting life.”
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.05,0:06:47.05,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, only God, Jehovah,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.05,0:06:50.01,Default,,0,0,0,,and his Son, Jesus Christ,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:50.01,0:06:53.72,Default,,0,0,0,,can usher us\Ninto everlasting dwelling places,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.72,0:06:56.27,Default,,0,0,0,,whether that be the heavenly Kingdom
Dialogue: 0,0:06:56.27,0:06:59.90,Default,,0,0,0,,or the Paradise earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.90,0:07:04.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, let’s make application\Nof this illustration.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.90,0:07:08.53,Default,,0,0,0,,How do we use\Nthe material things of this world
Dialogue: 0,0:07:08.53,0:07:12.66,Default,,0,0,0,,to make friends with Jehovah and Jesus?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:12.66,0:07:16.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Everything we own actually belongs to them.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:16.00,0:07:20.79,Default,,0,0,0,,However, each one of us\Nhas a measure of money and material assets
Dialogue: 0,0:07:20.79,0:07:24.09,Default,,0,0,0,,that we are free to use as we please.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:24.09,0:07:26.80,Default,,0,0,0,,So to make friends with Jehovah and Jesus,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.80,0:07:29.35,Default,,0,0,0,,we have to use those things in a way
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.35,0:07:32.31,Default,,0,0,0,,that brings their approval.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:32.31,0:07:35.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Our contributions\Ndon’t have to be in the form of cash.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.89,0:07:39.82,Default,,0,0,0,,In Jesus’ illustration,\Nthe debt was olive oil and wheat.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.82,0:07:43.65,Default,,0,0,0,,The unrighteous riches\Nmight even be coconuts.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.65,0:07:46.87,Default,,0,0,0,,A brother in southern India\Nowns a coconut farm.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.87,0:07:49.20,Default,,0,0,0,,He contributed a large number of coconuts
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.20,0:07:52.96,Default,,0,0,0,,to the local remote translation office.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:52.96,0:07:57.29,Default,,0,0,0,,He reasoned, “The office is going\Nto have to spend money and buy coconuts.”
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.29,0:08:00.05,Default,,0,0,0,,So his supplying the coconuts directly
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.05,0:08:02.42,Default,,0,0,0,,would help his contribution go further
Dialogue: 0,0:08:02.42,0:08:06.89,Default,,0,0,0,,than it would if he sold the coconuts\Nand gave the office the cash.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.89,0:08:09.68,Default,,0,0,0,,That is practical wisdom.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.68,0:08:12.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, if we go back to Luke chapter 16,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.64,0:08:15.31,Default,,0,0,0,,let’s look at verse 10.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:15.31,0:08:18.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Here it’s interesting that the principle
Dialogue: 0,0:08:18.15,0:08:22.57,Default,,0,0,0,,‘the person faithful in what is least\Nwill be faithful in much’
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.57,0:08:27.58,Default,,0,0,0,,was given in the context\Nof our use of material riches.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:27.58,0:08:30.79,Default,,0,0,0,,So we cannot take\Nthis responsibility lightly.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:30.79,0:08:33.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice what it says in verse 11.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.50,0:08:37.34,Default,,0,0,0,,It says: “Therefore,\Nif you have not proved yourselves faithful
Dialogue: 0,0:08:37.34,0:08:40.63,Default,,0,0,0,,“in connection with the unrighteous riches,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.63,0:08:43.64,Default,,0,0,0,,who will entrust you with what is true?”
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.60,0:08:50.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes, the way we use\Nour monetary riches or goods
Dialogue: 0,0:08:50.27,0:08:54.48,Default,,0,0,0,,will affect the extent\Nto which the things that are true,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.48,0:08:56.52,Default,,0,0,0,,such as Kingdom interests,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.52,0:08:59.07,Default,,0,0,0,,are entrusted to us.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.07,0:09:01.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Therefore,\Nlet’s remember the key point
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.95,0:09:06.03,Default,,0,0,0,,of Jesus’ illustration\Nof the unrighteous steward.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.03,0:09:10.25,Default,,0,0,0,,No matter how much or how little\Nof this world’s goods
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.25,0:09:12.38,Default,,0,0,0,,we have under our control,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:12.38,0:09:15.88,Default,,0,0,0,,we want to use them\Nto strengthen our relationship
Dialogue: 0,0:09:15.88,0:09:20.18,Default,,0,0,0,,with our best Friends,\NJehovah and Jesus.
